{"cursor":"3954","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"A 'lake pigment' is a pigment manufactured by precipitating a dye with an inert\nbinder, or \"mordant\", usually a metallic salt. This sense of lake is unconnected\nwith lake meaning body of water; it derives from the word lac (referring to a\nresinous secretion). \"lake, n.6\". OED Online. December 2011. Oxford\nUniversity Press. 25 January 2012.\n\nManufacturers and suppliers to artists and industry frequently omit the lake\ndesignation in the name. Many lake pigments are fugitive because the dyes\ninvolved are unstable when exposed to light.\n","linknr":133,"url":"Lake_pigment","recorded":1362560871,"links":11,"instances":["material","electromagnetic_radiation","physics"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Pigments"],"headings":["Chemistry","History and types","Notes"],"image":["//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/vector/images/search-ltr.png?303-4","//bits.wikimedia.org/images/wikimedia-button.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/poweredby_mediawiki_88x31.png"],"tags":[["binder","material"],["absorption","electromagnetic_radiation"],["reflection","physics"]],"members":["binder","absorption","reflection"],"related":["Pigment","Dye","Inert","Binder_(material)","Mordant","Metallic_salt","Lake","Lac","Fugitive_pigments","Chemical_stability","Light","Solubility","White","Neutral_color","Absorption_(electromagnetic_radiation)","Reflection_(physics)","Precipitate","Chalk","Clay","Bone","Calcium_carbonate","Calcium_phosphate","Barium_sulfate","Calcium_sulfate","Aluminium_hydroxide","Aluminium_oxide","Alumina","Ores","Indigo_dye","Woad","Egypt","Late_Middle_Ages","Europe","Indigofera_tinctoria","India","Rose_madder","Rubia","Quinacridone","Carmine","Cochineal","Central_America","South_America","Crimson_lake","Spanish_colonization_of_the_Americas","Aztec_Empire","Export","Silver","Carminic_acid","Organic_compound","Organic_synthesis","Artisans","Food_industry","Cosmetics"]}